<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes_for_Week_4:_4.2_Determinants_of_Price_Elasticity_of_Supply">Notes for Week 4: 4.2 Determinants of Price Elasticity of Supply</span></h2>
<p>Example: tobacco and houses; which one has the more inelastic supply?</p>
<p>o   Tobacco is more elastic: it takes longer to change production of housing than change production of tobacco</p>
<p>o   In general, manufacturing is very elastic (itâ€™s just enough to hire more people if production needs to increase and the change happens quickly)</p>
<p>The main determinant is the time scale (time needed to adjust)</p>
<p>In Brief, Price Elasticity of Supply(PES)of a product depends on:
a) Time taken for producing it
b) Cost of altering its supply
c) Feasibility of storing it</p>

